value.value: A tRNA sequence that has a tryptophan anticodon, and a 3' tryptophan binding region.
A tRNA sequence that has a tyrosine anticodon, and a 3' tyrosine binding region.
A tRNA sequence that has a valine anticodon, and a 3' valine binding region.
A small nuclear RNA molecule involved in pre-mRNA splicing and processing.

definition.value: This term is mapped to MGED. Do not obsolete without consulting MGED ontology.

value.value: Small nucleolar RNAs (snoRNAs) are short non-coding RNAs enriched in the nucleolus as components of small nucleolar ribonucleoproteins. They guide ribose methylation and pseudouridylation of rRNAs and snRNAs, and a subgroup regulate excision of rRNAs from rRNA precursor transcripts. snoRNAs may also guide rRNA acetylation and tRNA methylation, and regulate mRNA abundance and alternative splicing.

definition.value: Updated the definition of snoRNA (SO:0000275) from "A snoRNA (small nucleolar RNA) is any one of a class of small RNAs that are associated with the eukaryotic nucleus as components of small nucleolar ribonucleoproteins. They participate in the processing or modifications of many RNAs, mostly ribosomal RNAs (rRNAs) though snoRNAs are also known to target other classes of RNA, including spliceosomal RNAs, tRNAs, and mRNAs via a stretch of sequence that is complementary to a sequence in the targeted RNA." to "Small nucleolar RNAs (snoRNAs) are short non-coding RNAs enriched in the nucleolus as components of small nucleolar ribonucleoproteins. They guide ribose methylation and pseudouridylation of rRNAs and snRNAs, and a subgroup regulate excision of rRNAs from rRNA precursor transcripts. snoRNAs may also guide rRNA acetylation and tRNA methylation, and regulate mRNA abundance and alternative splicing." to acknowledge that some snoRNAs functionally localize to other compartments (cytoplasm or even secreted). See GitHub Issue #578.

value.value: Small, ~22-nt, RNA molecule that is the endogenous transcript of a miRNA gene (or the product of other non coding RNA genes). Micro RNAs are produced from precursor molecules (SO:0001244) that can form local hairpin structures, which ordinarily are processed (usually via the Dicer pathway) such that a single miRNA molecule accumulates from one arm of a hairpin precursor molecule. Micro RNAs may trigger the cleavage of their target molecules or act as translational repressors.
An attribute describing a sequence that is bound by another molecule.
A transcript that is bound by a nucleic acid.
A transcript that is bound by a protein.
A gene that is engineered.
A gene that is engineered and foreign.
An mRNA with a minus 1 frameshift.
A transposable_element that is engineered and foreign.
A gene that is foreign.
A sequence directly repeated at both ends of a defined sequence, of the sort typically found in retroviruses.
A gene that is a fusion.
A fusion gene that is engineered.
A repeat_region containing repeat_units of 2 to 10 bp repeated in tandem.

definition.value: A region of a repeating dinucleotide sequence (two bases).
A region of a repeating trinucleotide sequence (three bases).

value.value: A repetitive element that is engineered and foreign.
The sequence is complementarily repeated on the opposite strand. It is a palindrome, and it may, or may not be hyphenated. Examples: GCTGATCAGC, or GCTGA-----TCAGC.
A type of spliceosomal intron spliced by the U12 spliceosome, that includes U11, U12, U4atac/U6atac and U5 snRNAs.

definition.value: May have either GT-AC or AT-AC 5' and 3' boundaries.

value.value: A region of nucleic acid from which replication initiates; includes sequences that are recognized by replication proteins, the site from which the first separation of complementary strands occurs, and specific replication start sites.

Displacement loop; a region within mitochondrial DNA in which a short stretch of RNA is paired with one strand of DNA, displacing the original partner DNA strand in this region; also used to describe the displacement of a region of one strand of duplex DNA by a single stranded invader in the reaction catalyzed by RecA protein.

definition.value: Moved from is_a: SO:0000296 origin_of_replication to is_a: SO:0001411 biological_region after Terrence Murphy (INSDC) pointed out that the D loop can also refer to a loop in DNA repair, which is not an origin of replication. See GitHub Issue #417 (https://github.com/The-Sequence-Ontology/SO-Ontologies/issues/417)
A feature where there has been exchange of genetic material in the event of mitosis or meiosis
A location where recombination or occurs during mitosis or meiosis.
A location where a gene is rearranged due to recombination during mitosis or meiosis.
A feature where recombination has occurred for the purpose of generating a diversity in the immune system.

value.value: Recombination signal including J-heptamer, J-spacer and J-nonamer in 5' of J-region of a J-gene or J-sequence.
Part of the primary transcript that is clipped off during processing.
A modified nucleotide, i.e. a nucleotide other than A, T, C. G.
A nucleotide modified by methylation.
Regions of a few hundred to a few thousand bases in vertebrate genomes that are relatively GC and CpG rich; they are typically unmethylated and often found near the 5' ends of genes.
Attribute to describe a feature that has been experimentally verified.
A double-helical region of nucleic acid formed by base-pairing between adjacent (inverted) complementary sequences.
A repeat where the same sequence is repeated in the same direction. Example: GCTGA-followed by-GCTGA.
The first base where RNA polymerase begins to synthesize the RNA transcript.

definition.value: Added relationship is_a SO:0002309 core_promoter_element with the creation of core_promoter_element as part of GREEKC initiative August 2020 - Dave Sant.

value.value: A contiguous sequence which begins with, and includes, a start codon and ends with, and includes, a stop codon.
Complementary DNA; A piece of DNA copied from an mRNA and spliced into a vector for propagation in a suitable host.

definition.value: This term is mapped to MGED. Do not obsolete without consulting MGED ontology.

value.value: First codon to be translated by a ribosome.
In mRNA, a set of three nucleotides that indicates the end of information for protein synthesis.
Sequences within the intron that modulate splice site selection for some introns.
An mRNA with a plus 1 frameshift.

definition.value: A region of nucleotide sequence targeted by a nuclease enzyme that is found cleaved more than would be expected by chance.
Relationship to accessible_DNA_region added 11 Feb 2021. GREEKC pointed out that this is an assay based term, but we need a biological term for the accessible DNA. See GitHub Issue #531.

value.value: The first base to be translated into protein.
A nucleotide sequence that may be used to identify a larger sequence.
A primary transcript encoding a large ribosomal subunit RNA.
A short diagnostic sequence tag, serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE), that allows the quantitative and simultaneous analysis of a large number of transcripts.
The last base to be translated into protein. It does not include the stop codon.
